4.2.3.1 NPs Meaning of the NPs can be derived from the thematic roles in the sentence as presented in Chapter 16, [JM00] (due to lack of time this area remains unexplored at this moment). Additionally, we can infer some it from the Semantic Analysis (Section 3) and make up a template-like structure.
For example, [IS [y z]] can be used to represent a state of a noun z with a property of y. It can be nested ([IS [IS [dress ¡red¿] ¡torn¿]]) and can be stored in the event template list. This is roughly equivalent to the below, on which semantic restriction is imposed, however (the set of values z and y, or JJ and NN, can take):
NP -> JJ NP NP -> NN
Thus, for our little lexicon we could write a few entries for the simple noun phrases we have:
1. plain-single-state: {S, [IS [y z]]}
2. mixture: {S, [IS [y z] & IS [a b]]}
3. multi-state: {S, [IS [IS [x y] z]]}
